Date: 31 Oct 2000 12:23:10 -0500
From: Keith Steele <ksteele@usuhs.mil>

Some Answers to Previous Comments and Questions
------------------------------------------------
The demonstration of bird-to-bird transmission of West Nile virus (WNV) in
crows by Bob McLean and his group at the National Wildlife Health Center is
a significant, but not completely unexpected, finding. The possibility of
transmission of WNV unrelated to mosquitoes was the topic of significant
discussion at the West Nile virus Workshop in Tarrytown, NY last January.
In our study of West Nile virus in zoo birds and native crows in New York
City in 1999 (Vet Pathol 37:3, 2000), my colleagues and I demonstrated
virus in a wide variety of tissues and cell types, showing that the virus
was clearly pantropic in birds. Importantly, regarding the current
discussion, we showed using immunostaining, virus isolation and PCR that
virus was present in the intestines of 93% of cases and in the kidneys of
100% of cases tested. In addition, we noted virus in the bursa and in
feathers, however the numbers of these tissues analyzed was too few to make
valid conclusions from and include in our report.
The topic of transmission via infectious fecal material has been the
subject of previous ProMED discussions. I would only add that the
possibility of direct cloacal contact between crows and other birds should
also be considered as a possible mode of transmission. Hopefully, further
studies at the National Wildlife Health Center and elsewhere will clarify
the matter.
In a variety of newspaper articles and other information releases that I
have seen, a number of public health officials have asserted that the
handling of potentially infected birds was not considered hazardous, since
only mosquitoes could transmit the virus. The study by Dr. McLean, along
with previous reports that West Nile virus is a well-documented lab hazard,
should make it clear that a more conservative [precautionary approach to
the handling of birds is justified. The lack of evidence to date that bird
to human transmission has occurred does not preclude such an event in the
future, as the virus continues to spread in the U.S. The finding in our
study that tissues other than brain were more commonly infected than the
brain itself is also worth emphasis. It is my understanding that many of
the laboratories testing dead birds for WNV are doing so by removing the
brain for analysis. In our study, heart, kidney and intestines were more
frequently positive. In particular, crows and magpies appeared to have very
limited virus in the brain. Because these tissues can be more rapidly and
safely obtained than the brain, testing of heart, kidney or intestines
should provide a safer and quicker means of testing, with potentially fewer
false negative results.
That the strain of West Nile virus seen in the U.S. and in Israel since
1998 is unusually virulent and pantropic in birds is another matter that
should be the subject of future studies. Comparative testing of the U.S.
strain against strains responsible for previous outbreaks of West Nile
fever outside the U.S. is needed. The threat to certain species of birds by
the U.S. strain of West Nile virus is clearly one of the dramatic
consequences of its introduction here. While the effect on crows is
obvious, already threatened species like the bald eagle are also at risk.
We reported one fatal case in our study, and at least one additional bald
eagle was reported on ProMED-nail [so far unconfirmed - Mod.CP earlier
this year.
--
Keith Steele DVM
Diplomate, ACVP
<ksteele@usuhs.mil>
