Date: 1 Nov 2000 15:42:27 -0600
From: <linda_glaser@usgs.gov>

Statement from Dr. McLean of the USGS National Wildlife Health Center
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Regarding crow to crow transmission of WNV in an experimental setting:
Crows in the experimental study were housed in a certified biosafety level
3 facility. The animal isolation wing is a shower out containment area, the
supply air is single pass, rooms are under negative pressure and each room
is exhausted separately through a Hepa filter. The rooms housing the crows
were in the interior of the facility and were thoroughly disinfected with
paraformaldehyde prior to use for this study as all rooms are for
experimental studies. The floor of the experimental room was scrubbed every
day during the study.
All crows in the study were examined for the presence of ectoparasites upon
arrival and multiple times through the housing period with no parasites
observed. The birds also received 2 doses of a parasiticide during their
acclimation period. Crow carcasses were examined during the postmortem
diagnostic work-up for any evidence of ectoparasites. In addition, the
transmission and incubation periods were too short for the virus to have
been transmitted by ectoparasites.
--
Bob McLean, Ph.D.
Director
USGS National Wildlife Health Center
Madison, WI 53711
<robert_mclean@usgs.gov>
[Many of the questions posed in the previous posts have been answered by
these 2 informative communications. Dr. Steele's observations on the choice
of organs for sampling are particularly relevant for future surveillance
programs. Dr. McLean, whose experiments initiated this discussion, has the
last word. This thread is now cut. - Mod.CP
